Of course! To reverse a given text and add it to a document using Swift, you can modify your code as follows. Assuming you have the text you want to reverse and add to "myDocument", here's a simple code snippet to achieve that:

```swift
import Foundation

// Function to reverse a given string
func reverseString(_ text: String) -> String {
    return String(text.reversed())
}

// Function to write reversed text to a document
func writeReversedTextToFile(text: String, fileName: String) {
    let reversedText = reverseString(text)

    // Specify the file path
    let fileURL = FileManager.default.homeDirectoryForCurrentUser.appendingPathComponent(fileName)

    do {
        // Write the reversed text to the file
        try reversedText.write(to: fileURL, atomically: true, encoding: .utf8)
        print("Reversed text added to \(fileName) successfully.")
    } catch {
        print("Failed to write to file: \(error)")
    }
}

// Example text to reverse
let textToReverse = "Hello, Swift World!"

// Call the function with your text and document name
writeReversedTextToFile(text: textToReverse, fileName: "myDocument.txt")
```

Replace "Hello, Swift World!" with the text you want to reverse, and ensure that "myDocument.txt" is the name of the file you want to add the reversed text to. This script will write the reversed text to a file located in the user's home directory. Adjust the file path as necessary for your specific requirements.
